    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if i have an inductor with an inductive reactance of 50 ohms and a resistor with 30 ohms, how do i actually combine them to get the impedance? do i just add them together or is it more complicated than that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Since the resistor and the inductor oppose the current flow in different ways—resistance resists instantaneously, while inductive reactance resists based on changing current—you cannot simply add them. You must use the Pythagorean theorem to combine them, treating them as perpendicular components. The formula for impedance ($Z$) is $Z = \\sqrt{R^2 + X_L^2}$, where $R$ is resistance and $X_L$ is inductive reactance. Plugging in your values, $Z = \\sqrt{30^2 + 50^2}$, which results in an impedance of 58.31 ohms.",
      "source": "target",
