    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "oh okay, i see. so reactance is basically just a phase shift thing. what happens if i add a capacitor into that series circuit? does the math change if the reactance is negative or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, reactance is fundamentally tied to the phase shift between voltage and current in AC circuits. When you add a capacitor, you introduce capacitive reactance ($X_C$), and this value is subtracted from the inductive reactance when calculating impedance. The general formula then becomes $Z = \\sqrt{R^2 + (X_L - X_C)^2}$. The negative sign isn't technically part of the math, but rather the subtraction of the capacitive effect from the inductive effect to find the net reactance.",
      "source": "target",
